Documentation.name: NAFv4-ADMBw
Documentation.notes: The NATO Architecture Framework (NAF) is an Enterprise Architecture framework developed by the NATO and contributing nations. This MDG technologie ist based on version 4.0 of the framework. The architecture data model of the Bundeswehr (ADMBw) is the extension of the NAF according to the requirements of the Bundeswehr.
Documentation.categoryMappings: NAFv4-ADMBw Architecture Foundation Viewpoints=NAFv4Cat;NAFv4-ADMBw Concept Viewpoints=NAFv4Cat;NAFv4-ADMBw Service Specification Viewpoints=NAFv4Cat;NAFv4-ADMBw Logical Specification Viewpoints=NAFv4Cat;NAFv4-ADMBw Physical Resource Specification Viewpoints=NAFv4Cat;NAFv4-ADMBw Requirement Viewpoints=NAFv4Cat;

Stereotype.name: AchievedEffect
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that exists between an ActualState (e.g., observed/measured during testing) of an element that attempts to achieve a DesiredEffect and an Achiever.

Stereotype.name: Achiever
Stereotype.notes: An ActualResource, ActualProject or ActualEnterprisePhase that can deliver a DesiredEffect.

Stereotype.name: ActivityPerformableUnderCondition
Stereotype.notes: The ActualCondition under which an Activity is performed.

Stereotype.name: ActivitySupportsService
Stereotype.notes: Relation states that a process is necessary for the implementation of a service.

Stereotype.name: ActsUpon
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that something (subject) is acted upon by an OperationalActivity (activity).

Stereotype.name: ActualCondition
Stereotype.notes: An individual describing an actual situation with respect to circumstances under which an OperationalActivity, Function or ServiceFunction can be performed.

Stereotype.name: ActualConditionToActualResource
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that a actual resource is an actual situation.

Stereotype.name: ActualEnduringTask
Stereotype.notes: An actual undertaking recognized by an enterprise as being essential to achieving its goals - i.e. a strategic specification of what the enterprise does.

Stereotype.name: ActualEnterprisePhase
Stereotype.notes: The ActualState that describes the phase of an Enterprise endeavor.

Stereotype.name: ActualEnvironment
Stereotype.notes: The ActualState that describes the circumstances of an Environment.

Stereotype.name: ActualLocation
Stereotype.notes: The ActualState that describes a physical location, for example using text to provide an address, Geo-coordinates, etc.

Stereotype.name: ActualMeasurement
Stereotype.notes: An actual value that is applied to a Measurement.

Stereotype.name: ActualMeasurementSet
Stereotype.notes: A set of ActualMeasurements.

Stereotype.name: ActualMeasurementSetAppliesFor
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which actual measurement applies for an element.

Stereotype.name: ActualOrganization
Stereotype.notes: An actual formal or informal organizational unit, e.g. "Driving and Vehicle Licensing Agency", "UAF team Alpha".

Stereotype.name: ActualOrganizationalResource
Stereotype.notes: Abstract element for an ActualOrganization, ActualPerson or ActualPost.

Stereotype.name: ActualOrganizationRole
Stereotype.notes: An ActualOrganizationalResource that is applied to a ResourceRole.

Stereotype.name: ActualPerson
Stereotype.notes: An individual human being.

Stereotype.name: ActualPost
Stereotype.notes: An actual, specific post, an instance of a Post "type" - e.g., "President of the United States of America." where the Post would be president.

Stereotype.name: ActualProject
Stereotype.notes: A time-limited endeavor to provide a specific set of ActualResource that meet specific Capability needs.

Stereotype.name: ActualProjectConsults
Stereotype.notes: A relation that expresses that a project consults an OrganizationalResource.

Stereotype.name: ActualProjectDependency
Stereotype.notes: Relationship that is a dependency of a actualproject on a actualproject.

Stereotype.name: ActualProjectInforms
Stereotype.notes: A relation that expresses that a project informs an OrganizationalResource.

Stereotype.name: ActualProjectMilestone
Stereotype.notes: An event with a start date in a ActualProject from which progress is measured.

Stereotype.name: ActualProjectMilestoneRole
Stereotype.notes: An ActualProjectMilestone that is applied to a ProjectMilestoneRole.

Stereotype.name: ActualPropertySet
Stereotype.notes: A set or collection of Actual properties.

Stereotype.name: ActualResource
Stereotype.notes: Role in an Organisation, where the role carries the authority to undertake a function - through the ActualOrganizationalResource given the role has the responsibility.

Stereotype.name: ActualResourceNeededByActualProjectMilestone
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that an actual resource is needed by actual project milestones.

Stereotype.name: ActualResourceRelationship
Stereotype.notes: An actual resource flow existing between ActualResources (i.e. flow of data, people, materiel, or energy).

Stereotype.name: ActualResourceRole
Stereotype.notes: An instance of a ResourcePerformer.

Stereotype.name: ActualResourceToActualProjectMilestone
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that an actual resource is mapped to actual project milestones.

Stereotype.name: ActualResponsibleResource
Stereotype.notes: An abstract type grouping responsible OrganizationalResources.

Stereotype.name: ActualService
Stereotype.notes: An individual ServiceSpecification.

Stereotype.name: ActualServiceSpecificationRole
Stereotype.notes: An instance of a ServiceSpecification in context of a ServiceSpecification.

Stereotype.name: ActualState
Stereotype.notes: Abstract element that applies temporal extent to a set of elements realized as Instance Specifications.

Stereotype.name: AffectedActivity
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which resource is affected by a operational activity.

Stereotype.name: AffectedFunctions
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which function is affected by a resource.

Stereotype.name: AffectedResource
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which operational activity is affected by a resource.

Stereotype.name: Alias
Stereotype.notes: A metamodel Artifact used to define an alternative name for an element.

Stereotype.name: AlignsWithGoal
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that an element is aligned with a goal.

Stereotype.name: ArbitraryConnector
Stereotype.notes: Represents a visual indication of a connection used in high level operational concept diagrams.

Stereotype.name: ArchitecturalDescription
Stereotype.notes: An Architecture Description is a work product used to express the Architecture of some System Of Interest. It provides executive-level summary information about the architecture description in a consistent form to allow quick reference and comparison between architecture descriptions -- It includes assumptions, constraints, and limitations that may affect high-level decisions relating to an architecture-based work program.

Stereotype.name: ArchitecturalReference
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that specifies that one architectural description refers to another.

Stereotype.name: ArchitecturalSequence
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that specifies that one architectural description is the successor of another.

Stereotype.name: Architecture
Stereotype.notes: An abstract type that represents a generic architecture. Subtypes are OperationalArchitecture and ResourceArchitecture.

Stereotype.name: ArchitectureForProject
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that a architectural description belongs to a actual project.

Stereotype.name: ArchitectureMetadata
Stereotype.notes: Information associated with an ArchitecturalDescription, that supplements the standard set of tags used to summarize the Architecture. It states things like what methodology was used, notation, etc.

Stereotype.name: Asset
Stereotype.notes: Asset as applied to Security views, an abstract type that indicates the types of elements that can be considered as a subject for security analysis.
Stereotype.baseStereotypes: ConceptItem LocationHolder PropertySet SubjectOfForecast SubjectOfSecurityConstraint SysML1.4::block

Stereotype.name: AssetRole
Stereotype.notes: AssetRole as applied to Security views, an abstract element that indicates the type of elements that can be considered as a subject for security analysis in the particular context (currently no security viewpoints in the framework).

Stereotype.name: BoundaryCondition
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which environment is relevant to an resource exchange.

Stereotype.name: BusinessProcess
Stereotype.notes: An abstract type that represents a behavior or process (i.e. a Function or OperationalActivity) that can be performed by a Performer.

Stereotype.name: BWRequirement
Stereotype.notes: Abstract base class for requirements.

Tag.name: Uuid
Tag.description: Maschinenlesbare Nummerierung fr das Requirements Management Tool

Stereotype.name: Capability
Stereotype.notes: A high level specification of the enterprise's ability to execute a specified course of action.

Stereotype.name: CapabilityConfiguration
Stereotype.notes: A composite structure representing the physical and human resources (and their interactions) in an enterprise, assembled to meet a capability).

Stereotype.name: CapabilityDependency
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that asserts that one Capability is dependent from another.

Stereotype.name: CapabilityForTask
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that asserts that a Capability is required in order for an Enterprise to conduct a phase of an EnduringTask.

Stereotype.name: CapabilityGeneralization
Stereotype.notes: A CapabilityGeneralization is a taxonomic relationship between a more general Capability and a more specific Capability.

Stereotype.name: CapabilityRole
Stereotype.notes: A high level specification of the enterprise's ability to execute a specified course of action.

Stereotype.name: CapabilityRoleDependency
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that asserts that one CapabilityRole is dependent from another.

Stereotype.name: CapableElement
Stereotype.notes: An abstract type that represents a structural element that can perform behaviors (i.e. OperationalActivity).

Stereotype.name: Checks
Stereotype.notes: Relation that shows that an acceptance criterion (FitCriterion) is valid for a functional or non-functional requirement.

Stereotype.name: Classification
Stereotype.notes: Classification according to STANAG 1059.

Stereotype.name: Classified
Stereotype.notes: Relationship that indicates which classification an element has.

Stereotype.name: Command
Stereotype.notes: A type of ResourceExchange that asserts that one OrganizationalResource commands another.

Stereotype.name: Competence
Stereotype.notes: A specific set of abilities defined by knowledge, skills and aptitude.

Stereotype.name: CompetenceForRole
Stereotype.notes: A tuple used to associate an organizational role with a specific set of required competencies.

Stereotype.name: CompliesViewpoint
Stereotype.notes: Relationship that expresses that a view has been created according to the specifications of a viewpoint.

Stereotype.name: ConceptItem
Stereotype.notes: Abstract, an item which may feature in a HighLevelOperationalConcept.

Stereotype.name: ConceptRole
Stereotype.notes: Usage of a ConceptItem in the context of a HighLevelOperationalConcept.

Stereotype.name: Concern
Stereotype.notes: Interest in an EnterprisePhase (EnterprisePhase is synonym for System in ISO 42010) relevant to one or more of its stakeholders.

Stereotype.name: ConcernForActualEnterprisePhase
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which concerns are covered by an actual enterprise phase.

Stereotype.name: ConcernForView
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which concerns are covered by view.

Stereotype.name: ConcernForViewpoint
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which concerns are covered by viewpoint.

Stereotype.name: Condition
Stereotype.notes: A type that defines the Location, Environment and/or GeoPoliticalExtent.

Stereotype.name: ConflictsWith
Stereotype.notes: Relation that represents a conflict between two requirements.

Stereotype.name: ConformsTo
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that an UAFElement conforms to a standard.

Stereotype.name: ConsumedBy
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a service is consumed by a node. It is not required to know what provides the service.

Stereotype.name: Consumes
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that asserts that a service in someway contributes or assists in the execution of an OperationalActivity.

Stereotype.name: Control
Stereotype.notes: A type of ResourceExchange that asserts that one PhysicalResource controls another PhysicalResource (i.e. the driver of a vehicle controlling the vehicle speed or direction).

Stereotype.name: DataElement
Stereotype.notes: A formalized representation of data that is managed by or exchanged between resources.

Stereotype.name: DataElementStoredIn
Stereotype.notes: Relation says that a data is stored in software.

Stereotype.name: DataModel
Stereotype.notes: A structural specification of data types, showing relationships between them that is devoid of implementation detail. The type of data captured in the DataModel is described using the enumaration DataModelKind (Conceptual,Logical and Physical).

Stereotype.name: DataRole
Stereotype.notes: A usage of DataElement that exists in the context of an ResourceAsset. It also allows the representation of the whole-part aggregation of DataElements.

Stereotype.name: Definition
Stereotype.notes: A comment containing a description of an element in the architecture.

Stereotype.name: DerivedFrom
Stereotype.notes: Relation that shows that a functional or non-functional requirement is based on a process, role and task carrier, information element or other element.

Stereotype.name: DescribedBy
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that an architectural description describes an architecture.

Stereotype.name: DesiredEffect
Stereotype.notes: A tuple relating the Desirer (a Capability or OrganizationalResource) to an ActualState.

Stereotype.name: Desirer
Stereotype.notes: Abstract type used to group architecture elements that might desire a particular effect.

Stereotype.name: DocumentReference
Stereotype.notes: The element describes a regulation, instruction or a general document.

Stereotype.name: EnduringTask
Stereotype.notes: A type of template behavior recognized by an enterprise as being essential to achieving its goals - i.e. a template for a strategic specification of what the enterprise does.

Stereotype.name: Energy
Stereotype.notes: A representation of any kind of energy.

Stereotype.name: EnterpriseGoal
Stereotype.notes: A statement about a state or condition of the enterprise to be brought about or sustained through appropriate Means. An EnterpriseGoal amplifies an EnterpriseVision that is, it indicates what must be satisfied on a continuing basis to effectively attain the EnterpriseVision.

Stereotype.name: EnterprisePhase
Stereotype.notes: A current or future state of the wholeLifeEnterprise or another EnterprisePhase.

Stereotype.name: EnterpriseVision
Stereotype.notes: A Vision describes the future state of the enterprise, without regard to how it is to be achieved.

Stereotype.name: Environment
Stereotype.notes: A definition of the environmental factors in which something exists or functions. The definition of an Environment element can be further defined using EnvironmentKind.

Stereotype.name: EnvironmentalCondition
Stereotype.notes: Relationship that indicates under which environment an exhibits-relationship takes place.

Stereotype.name: EnvironmentalContext
Stereotype.notes: Relationship that indicates under which condition an measurement counts.

Stereotype.name: EnvironmentProperty
Stereotype.notes: A property of an Environment that is typed by a Condition. The kinds of Condition that can be represented are Location, GeoPoliticalExtentType and Environment.

Stereotype.name: Evaluates
Stereotype.notes: This relation states that an evaluation criterion (FulfilmentCriterion) can be assigned to a specific acceptance criterion (FitCriterion).

Stereotype.name: Exchange
Stereotype.notes: Abstract tuple, grouping OperationalExchanges and ResourceExchanges that exchange Resources.

Stereotype.name: ExchangeItem
Stereotype.notes: An abstract grouping for elements that defines the types of elements that can be exchanged between Assets and conveyed by an Exchange.

Stereotype.name: Exhibits
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that exists between a CapableElement and a Capability that it meets under specific environmental conditions.

Stereotype.name: Expresses
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that an architectural description includes the following architectures.

Stereotype.name: FieldedCapability
Stereotype.notes: An individual, fully-realized capability.

Stereotype.name: Finding
Stereotype.notes: An ascertainment made in the model, which relates to the methodology used, the subject under consideration, the tool or something else.

Stereotype.name: FitCriterion
Stereotype.notes: This element represents an acceptance criterion for a functional or non-functional requirement.

Stereotype.name: Forecast
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that specifies a transition from one Asset, Standard, Competence to another future one. It is related to an ActualEnterprisePhase to give it a temporal context.

Stereotype.name: ForecastPeriod
Stereotype.notes: Planning phase for which the forecast is valid.

Stereotype.name: FormStoredIn
Stereotype.notes: Relation states that a digital form is stored in software.

Stereotype.name: FulfilmentCriterion
Stereotype.notes: This element represents a criterion for evaluating the degree of implementation of a functional or non-functional requirement.

Stereotype.name: Function
Stereotype.notes: An Activity which is specified in the context to the ResourcePerformer (human or machine) that IsCapableToPerform it.

Stereotype.name: FunctionAction
Stereotype.notes: A call of a Function indicating that the Function is performed by a ResourceRole in a specific context.

Stereotype.name: FunctionalRequirement
Stereotype.notes: The element represents a functional requirement (what should the system / software be able to do?).

Stereotype.name: FunctionControlFlow
Stereotype.notes: An ActivityEdge that shows the flow of control between FunctionActions.

Stereotype.name: FunctionEdge
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that shows the flow of Resources (objects/data) between FunctionActions.

Stereotype.name: FunctionObjectFlow
Stereotype.notes: An ActivityEdge that shows the flow of Resources (objects/data) between FunctionActions.

Stereotype.name: FunctionSubject
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that a function uses certain resources.

Stereotype.name: GeoPoliticalExtentType
Stereotype.notes: A geospatial extent whose boundaries are defined by declaration or agreement by political parties.

Stereotype.name: GoalForActualEnterprisePhase
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which actual enterprisephase implements an enterprisegoal.

Stereotype.name: HighLevelOperationalConcept
Stereotype.notes: Describes the Resources and Locations required to meet an operational scenario from an integrated systems point of view. It is used to communicate overall quantitative and qualitative system characteristics to stakeholders

Stereotype.name: HostedOn
Stereotype.notes: Relation states that hardware (virtualized) or software is hosted on a virtualized platform or physical hardware.

Stereotype.name: Implements
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that defines how an element in the upper layer of abstraction is implemented by a semantically equivalent element (i.e. tracing the OperationalActivities to the Functions that implement them) in the lower level of abstraction.

Stereotype.name: ImplementsProtocol
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which protocol implements an architectural element.

Stereotype.name: Information
Stereotype.notes: A comment that describes the state of an item of interest in any medium or form -- and is communicated or received.

Stereotype.name: InformationElement
Stereotype.notes: An item of information that flows between OperationalPerformers and is produced and consumed by the OperationalActivities that the OperationalPerformers are capable to perform (see IsCapableToPerform).

Stereotype.name: InformationRole
Stereotype.notes: A usage of InformationElement that exists in the context of an OperationalAsset. It also allows the representation of the whole-part aggregation of InformationElements.

Stereotype.name: InteractionMessage
Stereotype.notes: An abstract type that groups several types of messages used in the InteractionScenario.

Stereotype.name: InteractionRole
Stereotype.notes: An abstract type that represents an individual participant in the InteractionScenario.

Stereotype.name: IsAccountableFor
Stereotype.notes: A relation that expresses that an OrganizationalResource is responsible for a resource, service or project in the context of an approval.

Stereotype.name: IsCapableToPerform
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that says that a capable element performs an activity or action.

Stereotype.name: IsDuplicateOf
Stereotype.notes: Relation that represents that two requirements convey the same content.

Stereotype.name: IsEquivalentToStandardElement
Stereotype.notes: Relationship that indicates that a model element corresponds to a catalog element.

Stereotype.name: IsResponsibleFor
Stereotype.notes: A relation that expresses that an OrganizationalResource is responsible for a resource, service or project.

Stereotype.name: JustifiedBy
Stereotype.notes: Relation states that an Constraint is derived from a reference (Reference, DocumentReference, SMEReference).

Stereotype.name: KnownResource
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a known ResourcePerformer constrains the implementation of the OperationalPerformer that plays the role in the LogicalArchitecture.

Stereotype.name: Location
Stereotype.notes: A specification of the generic area in which a LocationHolder is required to be located.

Stereotype.name: LocationHolder
Stereotype.notes: Abstract type, used to group elements that are allowed to be associated with a Location.

Stereotype.name: LocationType
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which location is assigned to a location holder.

Stereotype.name: MapsToCapability
Stereotype.notes: A tuple denoting that an Activity contributes to providing a Capability.

Stereotype.name: MeasurableElement
Stereotype.notes: Abstract type, grouping elements that can be measured by applying MeasurementSets to them.

Stereotype.name: Measurement
Stereotype.notes: A property of an element representing something in the physical world, expressed in amounts of a unit of measure.

Stereotype.name: MeasurementType
Stereotype.notes: A type of a property representing something in the physical world, expressed in amounts of a unit of measure.

Stereotype.name: Metadata
Stereotype.notes: A comment that can be applied to any element in the architecture. The attributes associated with this element details the relationship between the element and its related dublinCoreElement, metaDataScheme, category and name. This allows the element to be referenced using the Semantic Web.

Stereotype.name: MilestoneDependency
Stereotype.notes: A tuple between two ActualProjectMilestones that denotes one ActualProjectMilestone follows from another.

Stereotype.name: NaturalResource
Stereotype.notes: Type of physical resource that occurs in nature.

Stereotype.name: NeedsModificationOf
Stereotype.notes: Relation stats that a project makes adjustments to a resource.

Stereotype.name: NeedsResource
Stereotype.notes: Relation stats that a project needs a resource.

Stereotype.name: NeedsService
Stereotype.notes: A relation that expresses that a project needs a service

Stereotype.name: NonfunctionalRequirement
Stereotype.notes: The element represents a non-functional requirement (how should the system / software be able to do something?).

Stereotype.name: OperationalActivity
Stereotype.notes: An Activity that captures a logical process, specified independently of how the process is carried out.

Stereotype.name: OperationalActivityAction
Stereotype.notes: A call of an OperationalActivity in the context of another OperationalActivity.

Stereotype.name: OperationalActivityEdge
Stereotype.notes: A tuple that shows the flow of Resources (objects/information) between OperationalActivityActions.

Stereotype.name: OperationalAgent
Stereotype.notes: An abstract type grouping Operational Architecture and Operational Performer.

Stereotype.name: OperationalArchitecture
Stereotype.notes: A type used to denote a model of the Architecture, described from the Operational perspective.

Stereotype.name: OperationalArchitectureOfEnterprisePhase
Stereotype.notes: Relationship that says that in a actual enterprisephase an operational architecture is valid.

Stereotype.name: OperationalAsset
Stereotype.notes: An abstract element used to group the elements of OperationalAgent and InformationElement allowing them to own InformationRoles.

Stereotype.name: OperationalConnector
Stereotype.notes: A Connector that goes between OperationalRoles representing a need to exchange Resources. It can carry a number of OperationalExchanges.

Stereotype.name: OperationalConstraint
Stereotype.notes: A Rule governing a logical architectural element i.e. OperationalPerformer, OperationalActivity, InformationElement etc.

Tag.name: Id
Tag.description: Lesbare laufende Nummerierung fr den Forderungskatalog

Tag.name: Uuid
Tag.description: Maschinenlesbare Nummerierung fr das Requirements Management Tool

Stereotype.name: OperationalControlFlow
Stereotype.notes: An ActivityEdge that shows the flow of control between OperationalActivityActions.

Stereotype.name: OperationalExchange
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a flow can exist between OperationalPerformers (i.e. flows of information, people, materiel, or energy).

Stereotype.name: OperationalExchangeItem
Stereotype.notes: An abstract grouping for elements that defines the types of elements that can be exchanged between OperationalPerformers and conveyed by an OperationalExchange.

Stereotype.name: OperationalInterface
Stereotype.notes: A declaration that specifies a contract between the OperationalPerformer it is related to, and any other OperationalPerformers it can interact with.

Stereotype.name: OperationalMessage
Stereotype.notes: Message for use in an Operational Event-Trace which carries any of the subtypes of OperationalExchange.

Stereotype.name: OperationalMessageFlow
Stereotype.notes: A ProcessMessageFlow that shows the flow of message between OperationalActivityActions of different ActivityPartitions like Pools.

Stereotype.name: OperationalMethod
Stereotype.notes: behavioral feature of a OperationalPerformer whose behavior is specified in an OperationalActivity.

Stereotype.name: OperationalObjectFlow
Stereotype.notes: An ActivityEdge that shows the flow of Resources (objects/information) between OperationalActivityActions.

Stereotype.name: OperationalParameter
Stereotype.notes: A type that represents inputs and outputs of an OperationalActivity. It is typed by an OperationalExchangeItem.

Stereotype.name: OperationalPerformer
Stereotype.notes: A logical entity that IsCapableToPerform OperationalActivities which produce, consume and process Resources.

Stereotype.name: OperationalPort
Stereotype.notes: An interaction point for an OperationalAgent through which it can interact with the outside environment and which is defined by an OperationalInterface.

Stereotype.name: OperationalRole
Stereotype.notes: Usage of a OperationalPerformer or OperationalArchitecture in the context of another OperationalPerformer or OperationalArchitecture. Creates a whole-part relationship.

Stereotype.name: OperationalSignal
Stereotype.notes: An item of information that flows between OperationalPerformers and is produced and consumed by the OperationalActivities that the OperationalPerformers are capable of performing (see IsCapableToPerform).

Stereotype.name: OperationalSignalProperty
Stereotype.notes: A property of an OperationalSignal typed by OperationalExchangeItem. It enables OperationalExchangeItem e.g. InformationElement to be passed as arguments of the OperationalSignal.

Stereotype.name: OperationalStateDescription
Stereotype.notes: A state machine describing the behavior of a OperationalPerformer, depicting how the OperationalPerformer responds to various events and the actions.

Stereotype.name: Organization
Stereotype.notes: A group of OrganizationalResources (Persons, Posts, Organizations and Responsibilities) associated for a particular purpose.

Stereotype.name: OrganizationalResource
Stereotype.notes: An abstract type for Organization, Person Post and Responsibility.

Stereotype.name: OriginatesFrom
Stereotype.notes: Relation that derives an element in the architectural model from a reference (Reference, DocumentReference, SMEReference).

Stereotype.name: OwnedMilestone
Stereotype.notes: Relationship that expresses that actual project has a actual milestone.

Stereotype.name: OwnsActualMeasurementSet
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which actual measurement set an element owns.

Stereotype.name: OwnsMeasurement
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which measurement or measurement type an element owns.

Stereotype.name: OwnsProcess
Stereotype.notes: A dependency relationship denoting that an ActualOrganizationResource owns an OperationalActivity.

Stereotype.name: PaperForm
Stereotype.notes: Form is a digitized or digitizable document, for example a scanned document.

Stereotype.name: PartOfCatalogue
Stereotype.notes: This relation states that a category (RequirementCategory) belongs to a requirements catalog (RequirementCatalogue).

Stereotype.name: PartOfCategory
Stereotype.notes: This relation states that his functional or non-functional requirement belongs to a category (RequirementCategory) of the requirements catalog.

Stereotype.name: PerformsInContext
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that says that a role performs an activity or action. It indicates that the action can be carried out by the role when used in a specific context or configuration.

Stereotype.name: Person
Stereotype.notes: A type of a human being used to define the characteristics that need to be described for ActualPersons (e.g. properties such as address, telephone number, nationality, etc).

Stereotype.name: PhysicalArchitectureOfEnterprisePhase
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that an actual enterprise phase has resource architectures.

Stereotype.name: PhysicalLocation
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that a location holder operates in an actual location.

Stereotype.name: PhysicalResource
Stereotype.notes: An abstract type defining physical resources (i.e. OrganizationalResource, ResourceArtifact and NaturalResource).

Stereotype.name: Post
Stereotype.notes: A type of job title or position that a person can fill (e.g. Lawyer, Solution Architect, Machine Operator or Chief Executive Officer).

Stereotype.name: PostRole
Stereotype.notes: A usage of a post in the context of another OrganizationalResource. Creates a whole-part relationship.

Stereotype.name: ProblemDomain

Stereotype.name: View

Stereotype.name: Viewpoint

Stereotype.name: ViewpointsInArchitecturalDescription
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that an architectural description includes the following viewpoints.

Stereotype.name: ViewpointToStakeholder

Stereotype.name: ViewsInArchitecturalDescription
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses that an architectural description includes the following views.

Stereotype.name: VisionForActualEnterprisePhase
Stereotype.notes: A relationship that expresses which actual enterprisephase implements an enterprisevision.

Stereotype.name: WholeLifeConfiguration
Stereotype.notes: A set of VersionedElements.

Stereotype.name: WholeLifeEnterprise
Stereotype.notes: A WholeLifeEnterprise is a purposeful endeavor of any size involving people, organizations and supporting systems. It is made up of TemporalParts and StructuralParts.

Stereotype.name: A1 - Meta-Data Definitions
Stereotype.notes: Architectures, particularly large ones, usually require meta-data tags to aid with searching and discovery.

Stereotype.name: A2 - Architecture Products
Stereotype.notes: The A2 Viewpoint specifies the structure of an architecture, and the products that describe the architecture. Each product may correspond to an architecture view. This viewpoint also traces the architectures onto the Enterprise Phases they correspond to (see also C2 Enterprise Vision) and identifies the key stakeholders, their concerns and the products that address those concerns (from ISO/IEC/IEEE Standards).

Stereotype.name: A3 - Architecture Correspondence
Stereotype.notes: ISO/IEC/IEEE42010 introduces the idea of architecture correspondence and correspondence rules. Quoting from ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010; A correspondence defines a relation between AD (Architecture Description) elements. Correspondences are used to express architecture relations of interest within an architecture description (or between architecture descriptions). Correspondences can be governed by correspondence rules. Correspondence rules are used to enforce relations within an architecture description (or between architecture descriptions).

Stereotype.name: A4 - Methodology Used
Stereotype.notes: The A4 Viewpoint specifies the methodology used for the architecting activities. This methodology is described in NAFv4 Chapter 2. The content of the A4 viewpoint can also be modeled in the A1 viewpoint.

Stereotype.name: A5 - Architecture Status
Stereotype.notes: Since NAFv3.0, it has been possible to assign version numbers to views and specify their approval dates. In NAFv4.0, this is integrated with the meta-models generic project and milestone approach so that architecture releases are tracked against the architecture delivery project. The content of the A5 viewpoint can also be modeled in the A1 viewpoint.

Stereotype.name: A6 - Architecture Version
Stereotype.notes: Where the A5 Viewpoint shows the current version number and approval status for the architecture, the A6 Viewpoint shows the complete history of the architecture.

Stereotype.name: A7 - Architecture Compliance
Stereotype.notes: The A7 Viewpoint gives the overall specification of architecture meta-data.

Stereotype.name: A8 - Standards
Stereotype.notes: The A8 Viewpoint encompasses both technical and non-technical standards. The standards specified in the A8 view can be applied across the architecture to a variety of structural and behavioural elements. Standards are essential to the coherent running of businesses and to the delivery of reliable, interoperable systems.

Stereotype.name: Ar - Architecture Roadmap
Stereotype.notes: The Ar Viewpoint shows the history of the architecture project as well as its future direction.

Stereotype.name: C1 - Capability Taxonomy
Stereotype.notes: The C1 Viewpoint specifies all the capabilities that are referenced throughout one or more architectures i.e. one C1 may provide the definitive list of capabilities for a number of logical and resource architectures. The capabilities may be organised into specialisation hierarchies (taxonomies). Measures of Effectiveness (MoE) may be specified for each capability. Note that MoEs are inherited down a capability taxonomy.

Stereotype.name: C2 - Enterprise Vision
Stereotype.notes: The purpose of the C2 Viewpoint is to provide a strategic context for the capabilities described in the architecture and to specify the scope for the architecture. The C2 Viewpoint is high-level and describes the vision, goals, enduring tasks and capabilities using terminology that is easily understood by non-technical readers.

Stereotype.name: C3 - Capability Dependencies
Stereotype.notes: The C3 Viewpoint is intended to provide a means of analysing the dependencies between capabilities and between capability clusters. The composition of capabilities (into clusters) is logical and the purpose of the clusters is to guide enterprise management.

Stereotype.name: C4 - Standard Processes
Stereotype.notes: The C4 Viewpoint specifies Standard Operational Activities that can be re-used across multiple logical architectures (e.g. in L4, Logical Activities).

Stereotype.name: C5 - Effects
Stereotype.notes: The purpose of the C5 Viewpoint is to describe the operational effect of the capabilities, activities and services according to the expected goals. The C5 Viewpoint is high-level description that should be easily understood by non-technical readers.

Stereotype.name: C7 - Performance Parameters
Stereotype.notes: In the C7 Viewpoint the capability requirements (and existing capabilities) can be expressed in terms of Measures of Effectiveness (MoEs). These are high-level metrics used to judge the level of capability.

Stereotype.name: C8 - Planning Assumptions
Stereotype.notes: The C8 Viewpoint is concerned with identification and description of assumptions that have been made for the implementation of capabilities. Assumptions can be expressed by means of requirements.

Stereotype.name: Cr - Capability Roadmap
Stereotype.notes: The Cr Viewpont supports the Capability Audit process by providing a method to identify gaps or duplications in capability provision. Cr indicates capability increments, which are derived from delivery milestones within acquisition projects.

Stereotype.name: L1 - Node Types
Stereotype.notes: The L1 Viewpoint defines all of the Nodes that will appear in a Logical Architecture. Nodes are elements of capability assembled and orchestrated in the Logical Architecture (see L2 - Logical Scenario and L4 - Logical Activities views). The levels of capability provided by each node are expressed as Measures of Performance (MoPs) and these may be dependent on the environments in which the Node is required to operate.

Stereotype.name: L2 - Logical Scenario
Stereotype.notes: The L2 Viewpoint specifies Nodes (elements of capability) in context of each other. The context is usually expressed in terms of the information that flows between the nodes (e.g. the information flow requirements between capabilities in a given scenario) but may also be flows of materiel, human resource or energy.

Stereotype.name: L3 - Node Interactions
Stereotype.notes: L3 is used to provide further detail of the interoperability requirements associated with the operational capability of interest. The focus is on logical flows that cross the capability boundary. Although the primary purpose of the L3 Viewpoint is to specify information exchanges, the L3 may also list flows of materiel, energy and human resources.

Stereotype.name: L4 - Logical Activities
Stereotype.notes: The L4 Viewpoint describes the operational activities that are being conducted within the mission or scenario. These activities are defined at a logical, solution-neutral level so as to enable different solutions in the physical layer. The L4 Viewpoint describes the activities associated with the logical architecture, as well as the:

Stereotype.name: L5 - Logical States
Stereotype.notes: The L5 Viewpoint specifies the typical states a node may have and the possible transitions between those states (i.e. changes of state). Triggers for state changes may also be defined. Actions may be associated with a given state or with the transition between states in response to stimuli (e.g. triggers and events).

Stereotype.name: L6 - Logical Sequence
Stereotype.notes: Operational Event-Trace Descriptions, sometimes called sequence diagrams, event scenarios or timing diagrams, allow the tracing of interactions between nodes in a scenario or critical sequence of events. The node interactions usually correspond to flows of information but may describe flows of energy, materiel or people specified in the L2, Logical Scenario.

Stereotype.name: L7 - Information Model
Stereotype.notes: The L7 Viewpoint is used to document the business information. It describes the information that can be exchanged along the logical flows in the architecture, specified in L3 Node Interactions.

Stereotype.name: L8 - Logical Constraints
Stereotype.notes: The L8 Viewpoint is used to constrain the logical architecture without forcing a particular solution. L8 is used for rules which are not expressed as behavioural models, interactions or measures of effectiveness, i.e. they are textual statements of requirements that constrain the architecture.

Stereotype.name: Lr - Lines of Development
Stereotype.notes: The Lr Viewpoint is primarily intended to support the acquisition process across multiple projects or programmes, highlighting dependencies the logical dependencies between capabilities, projects and the integration of all lines of development to achieve a successfully integrated military capability. Use of the Lr Viewpoint should support the management of capability delivery and be aligned with Cr, Capability Roadmap.

Stereotype.name: L2-L3 - Logical Concept
Stereotype.notes: The L2-L3 Viewpoint is concerned with providing an executive level, scenario-based communication of the architecture purpose, scope and content.

Stereotype.name: P1 - Resource Types
Stereotype.notes: The P1 Viewpoint collects together all the Resource Types in the architecture together with a depiction of their performance characteristics. P1 also provides a summary of the technologies and competencies that impact on the Resources that constitute the architecture.

Stereotype.name: P2 - Resource Structure
Stereotype.notes: The P2 Viewpoint links together the operational and physical architecture viewpoints by depicting how types of Resource are structured and interact to realize the logical architecture specified in L2, Logical Scenario. The P2 Viewpoint may represent the realization of a requirement specified in a L2 (i.e. in a to-be architecture) and so there may be many alternative Resource viewpoint suites that could realize the operational requirement. Alternatively, in an as-is architecture, a L2 may just be a simplified, logical representation of the P2 Viewpoint to allow communication of key information flows to non-technical stakeholders.

Stereotype.name: P3 - Resource Connectivity
Stereotype.notes: The networks and pathways documented in a P3 Viewpoint represent the physical implementation of the logical flows identified in a L2, Logical Scenario, or L3, Node Interactions View.

Stereotype.name: P4 - Resource Functions
Stereotype.notes: The Functionality Description provides detailed information regarding the allocation of functions to resources, and flows between Resource Functions. The P4 Viewpoint is the Physical Resource counterpart to the L4 Logical Activities Viewpoint.

Stereotype.name: P5 - Resource States
Stereotype.notes: The P5 Viewpoint identifies the states a Resource can be, the allowable changes between those states, and the stimuli (e.g. triggers and events) that cause the state changes.

Stereotype.name: P6 - Resource Sequence
Stereotype.notes: The P6 Viewpoint is valuable for moving to the next level of detail from the initial solution design, to help define a sequence of functions and Resource Interactions, and to ensure that each participating Resource or Port has the necessary information, at the right time, in order to perform its assigned functionality.

Stereotype.name: P7 - Data Model
Stereotype.notes: The P7 Viewpoint is one of the architectural products closest to actual system design in the NAF. It is used to describe how the information represented in the L7 Logical Data Model Viewpoint is implemented.

Stereotype.name: P8 - Resource Constraints
Stereotype.notes: The P8 Viewpoint describes constraints on the Resources, Resource Functions, data and communications that make up a Physical Architecture.

Stereotype.name: Pr - Configuration Management
Stereotype.notes: The Pr Viewpoint provides an overview of how Resource Assets change over time (note that NAF v3.1 only allowed for Capability Configurations whereas now this is opened up to all Resource Types). It shows the structure of different versions of Resource Assets (usually Capability Configurations or Service Implementations) mapped against a timeline.

Stereotype.name: L4-P4 - Activity To Function Mapping
Stereotype.notes: The L4-P4 Viewpoint depicts the mapping of Resource Functions (and optionally, the resources that provide them) to operational activities and/or service functions. For operational activities it thus identifies the transformation of an operational need into a purposeful action performed by a system or solution. For service functions it provides the link between the services used at the operational level and the specific Resource Functions provided by the resources supporting the services.

Stereotype.name: S1 - Service Taxonomy
Stereotype.notes: The purpose of the S1 Viewpoint is to provide a governance structure for a Service-Oriented Architecture. Along with S3, Service Interfaces, it specifies a standard library of service specifications for an enterprise, to which service implementers are expected to conform.

Stereotype.name: S2 - Service Structure
Stereotype.notes: The S2 Viewpoint is concerned with identification and description of how services are structured to create a higher-aggregated service. To provide highlevel views, dependencies to other services, nodes and resources as well as service interfaces and service functions can be represented.

Stereotype.name: S3 - Service Interfaces
Stereotype.notes: The S3 Viewpoint is concerned with the identification and definition of service interfaces.

Stereotype.name: S4 - Service Functions
Stereotype.notes: The S4 Viewpoint is the key behavioural specification for services. Equivalent in nature to L4, Logical Activities and P4, Resources Functions, it specifies a set of functions that a service implementation is expected to perform. Implementation of that behaviour is represented in P4, Resource Functions, and L4-P4, Activity to Function Mapping.

Stereotype.name: S5 - Service States
Stereotype.notes:
The S5 Viewpoint is a specification of the allowable states of a service, and the possible transitions between them. This specification constrains how implementations of the service will behave.
It is, though, generally considered a good practice to make services stateless - i.e. consumers of a service are not aware of what state the service is in.

Stereotype.name: S6 - Service Interactions
Stereotype.notes: Service Interaction Descriptions, sometimes called sequence diagrams, event scenarios or timing diagrams, allow the tracing of interactions between services in a composition or critical sequence of events.

Stereotype.name: S7 - Service Interface Parameters
Stereotype.notes: Specifies the interfaces that a service provides and uses, defines which services are compatible with which other services.

Stereotype.name: S8 - Service Policy
Stereotype.notes: The S8 Viewpoint specifies constraints against services to which implementations must conform.

Stereotype.name: Sr - Service Roadmap
Stereotype.notes: The Sr Viewpoint supports the Service Audit process by providing a method to identify gaps or duplications in service provision. Sr indicates service lifetime evolutions, which are derived from delivery milestones within acquisition projects.

Stereotype.name: C1-S1 - Capability to Service Mapping
Stereotype.notes: A C1-S1 Viewpoint presents a simple mapping of services to capabilities, showing which services contribute to which capability.

Stereotype.name: R2 - Requirement Catalogue
Stereotype.notes: The R2 represents a catalog of requirements in the architectural model. For this purpose, categories can be created in which the functional and non-functional requirements can be grouped.

Stereotype.name: R3 - Requirement Dependencies
Stereotype.notes: The R3 is used to show dependencies between different requirements.

Stereotype.name: R7 - Requirement Derivation
Stereotype.notes: The R7 assigns functional and non-functional requirements to the demanding architectural elements. In addition, information about the planned realization can be shown.

Stereotype.name: R8 - Requirement Fulfilment
Stereotype.notes: The R8 is used to determine and map acceptance and evaluation criteria for the individual functional and non-functional requirements.

Stereotype.name: Rr - Requirement Realization
Stereotype.notes: In the Rr, requirements are assigned to the realizing architectural elements.
